title.children: 'A drop in the ocean of need': WHO calls for more aid to Gaza as trucks wait to cross border

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The UN humanitarian office says it is in "deep and advanced negotiations with all relevant sides" to open a humanitarian corridor into Gaza "as quickly as possible". "We are encouraged by reports that the sides are nearing an agreement on the modalities, and that a first aid delivery to Gaza is due to start in the next day or so," the UN office says. Humanitarian organisations have been stockpiling supplies in northern Egypt ahead of the planned opening of the Rafah crossing — the only road into Gaza not controlled by Israel. Egypt previously said it never formally closed the crossing but that "repeated bombings" by Israel on the Gaza side of the crossing had put it out of operation. The crossing was expected to open today and allow 20 trucks to deliver aid into the Palestinian enclave.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Gaza aid to be delivered 'in the next day or so,' UN says

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Israel plans to evacuate residents from the town of Kiryat Shmona near its border with Lebanon, the Defense Ministry has announced. Residents of the town near the border will be moved to state-subsidised guesthouses, the ministry said. Kiryat Shmona is in Israel's north and just a few kilometres from the border, across which Israeli troops and militants in Lebanon have been exchanging fire. In a separate announcement posted on social media, the Israeli Air Force said overnight it had "eliminated a terrorist" in Lebanese territory and destroyed a number of military targets belonging to Hezbollah.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Israel announces plans to evacuate residents of border town near Lebanon

children.content: Israel plans to evacuate residents from the town of Kiryat Shmona near its border with Lebanon, the Defense Ministry has announced.
Residents of the town near the border will be moved to state-subsidised guesthouses, the ministry said.
Kiryat Shmona is in Israel's north and just a few kilometres from the border, across which Israeli troops and militants in Lebanon have been exchanging fire.

In a separate announcement posted on social media, the Israeli Air Force said overnight it had "eliminated a terrorist" in Lebanese territory and destroyed a number of military targets belonging to Hezbollah.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Food, medicines, water purifiers, hygiene products and blankets: the aid has been piling up in Egypt's Sinai region at El Arish airport, which even opened an extra landing strip to cope with deliveries. Rafah, the border crossing into Gaza that Egypt had promised to open on Friday, is a few dozen kilometres to the east. It is the only crossing into the blockaded Palestinian territory that is not controlled by Israel. Ahmed Ali, head of the Egyptian Red Crescent, told AFP his organisation receives "two to three planes of aid a day, chartered by humanitarian agencies or states", who want to send food, water or medical supplies to the 2.4 million Palestinians in Gaza. As soon as aid is dropped off on the tarmac, the shipments are loaded onto trucks. Egyptian state-linked broadcaster Al Qahera News said the Rafa crossing would open on Friday. But later Egypt said it needed more time, to repair the roads that connect its territory to Gaza after four Israeli bombings of the crossing. In the meantime, pallets loaded with aid are stored in warehouses in El Arish, the capital of North Sinai, said Ali. As soon as the green light is given, 250 volunteers are ready to transport them to the border. The deal struck by US President Joe Biden with Israel and Egypt will allow in 20 trucks. The emergencies director of the World Health Organization has called it "a drop in the ocean of need". "It should be 2,000 trucks," Michael Ryan said. AFP
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'It should be 2,000 trucks': At the gates of Gaza, aid piles up in Egypt
